field_edited_text.value:
Illustrated below are sevefal examples of the services which Maryland’s Free-
way and Expressway system provide to motorists throughout the State. From
left to right, top to bottom they include:

. The Baltimore Beltway. Steady streams of homeward bound motorists now
enjoy the benefits of freeway lighting on this important metropolitan belt.
Edison said ‘“‘light is the world’s best policeman.” This is true on the freeway
where the lighted roadway ahead adds another measure of traffic safety to the
beltway’s already impressive record of 1.1 deaths per 100 million miles travelled
as compared with a national average of 2.6 for freeways.

. The Capital Beltway. The mercury-vapor lamps fade with the coming of
daylight to reveal the beauty of this freeway circling Washington. Expert land-
scaping, designed into the road from the earliest planning stage gives the motor-
ist a most pleasant as well as practical trip.

. The juncture of two mighty superhighways — the Baltimore Beltway and the
John F. Kennedy Memorial Highway — provide the setting for this fully directional
interchange designed to give the motorist quick and easy access in switching
from one road to the other.

. Mighty machines and the men who run them mold steel, concrete and as-
phalt into tomorrow’s freeway. New highways not only help the economy of
the area they serve; the very act of construction creates many manhours of work
for builders and those who manufacture and provide materials.

MARYLAND-the FREEway State



. The symbol of the Interstate System reminds travelers that many of Mary-
land’s freeways are a part of this gigantic 41,000-mile network which, when com-
pleted in 1972, will join our State with every other section of the country. The
State Roads Commission now has under contract 84 percent of the Interstate
mileage for which it is responsible. Maryland stands proudly among the top five
states in percentage of Interstate freeway open to traffic.

- A courteous reminder to those who travel our roads meets the motorist en-
tering Maryland. Although Maryland'’s traffic death toll reached a record 694 in
1965, the frequency of fatal accidents on freeways and expressways remained
low throughout the system. This proves once again that this type of highway is
the safest method of road travel.

- The Appalachian Corridor. A new freeway will open the mountains of West-
ern Maryland to development, and place the manufacturing centers of the Ohio
River Valley next door to the Port of Baltimore and the commercial markets of our
State. Running from Hancock, where I-70 turns North into Pennsylvania, this
freeway will move West through Appalachia to Morgantown, West Virginia.

. An example of what future travel through Western Maryland will be like, this
newly opened section of I-70 just West of Clear Springs combines the wild beauty
of the mountains with swift arrival at your destination.

. This sign along the John F. Kennedy Memorial Highway reminds motorists
to stop at the famed Maryland House restaurant and service area. Other signs
are located at frequent intervals throughout the freeway and expressway system
pointing out to the motorist that **Food, Gas and Lodging'" are available nearby.
